Kuni_393,Kuni,kuni1263,Kuni,kse,Papunesia,-8.66368,146.874,Austronesian,"Alan Jones, Barnabas Maua, Malcolm Ross",https://abvd.eva.mpg.de/austronesian/language.php?id=393,Janet Moody,,"All stems functioning as finite verbs are preceded by a subject-marking clitic or prefix. In the third person (the usual citation form) this can be either e- or i-. The former marks the verb as irrealis while the latter is the characteristic form for narratives. I have chosen to represent all verbs with the irrealis e- form, for consistency.

All noun stems that may be inalienably possessed (body parts, relations, etc.) are represented with the 3rd person suffix marker -na, indexing a third person """"possessor"""" - such stems, when used as adjectives, as a general rule take a person-marking suffix
column2: on some stems this has become fossilised, while others resist it (possibly only in some uses). Hyphenation indicates affixation
column3: even the subject markers are represented here as prefixes, though the argument for this has yet to be made.","@

Kubokota_508,Kubokota,kubo1244,Kubokota,ghn,Papunesia,,,Austronesian,Mary Raymond,https://abvd.eva.mpg.de/austronesian/language.php?id=508,Mary Raymond,,"Kubokota and Luqa are very closely related although there are some grammatical differences and, I feel, more lexical differences than this word list suggests (Kubokota has a lot of borrowings from Bilua, a neighbouring Papuan language).

Orthography: q = voiced velar stop, v = voiced bilabial fricative, ng = velar nasal, ny = palatal nasal, g = voiced velar fricative, j = voiced palatal affricate. All voiced stops and affricates are prenasalized.","@

1. geminate consonants and vowels do not represent independent phonological segments,
